m in return for increased inclusion within the political system.Key FeaturesDraws on a wide range of original data, including interviews with former leading British and Irish politicians and civil servants; original material produced by republicanism over a 40-year period; and the latest available archival material from Britain, Ireland and Northern IrelandReassesses British policy towards the management of the conflict in Northern IrelandRigorously evaluates where Sinn Féin stands today in terms of achieving its goal of a united IrelandRaises important implications for how other non-state armed groups moderate, for the study of state responses to violent separatism and for studies of comparative peace processes  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 4aPolitics. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Political Parties.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311078140340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147442055640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474420556423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474420556/original  a978-3-11-078140-3  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK